Croatia is planning a nuclear treatment facility, Bosnians protest.
On Friday, hundreds of people gathered in northwestern Bosnia and Herzegovina to protest the Croatian plan to store some of the waste from the region's only nuclear power plant near a river known for its beautiful nature near the border with Bosnia.
The demonstrators of the Bosnian town of Novi Grad strongly urged Croatia to abandon the plan to store the site of the barracks in Trugovska Gola, and vow to fight the plan.
The facility will store waste from the Kursico nuclear power plant.
The Bosnians, who wrote, "Don't take away a healthy future," and "Don't stop it firmly."
We must oppose it.
Miloslav Driaka, head of the municipality of Novi Grad, said to the crowd.
We must fight to protect our lives and the Una River.
The Kursko Nuclear Power Plant, which began operation in the 1980s, is located in Slovenia and is jointly owned by Croatia.
Government officials from both countries will discuss the expansion of waste treatment facilities next week.
Croatian national broadcasters reported on Friday that Croatia had yet to decide whether to build its own storage facility or to pay for the waste of Croatia that Slovenia would be treated at newly constructed facilities.
Croatian Minister of Environmental Protection and Energy Tomislav Chorich told the announcer that Croatia is also facing problems in the disposal of public waste from schools, hospitals and prisons, and wants to find a complete solution.
In Bosnia, activists, officials, and residents of all ethnic groups in the country claimed that Croatia would find another location on its own near the nuclear power plant.
"Why would the pockets of Bosnian trousers - the Turkovska gola - be the best place in Croatia?"
