Pope, warning IT representatives that AI development is based on public interests
On Friday, Pope Francis warned IT representatives, diplomats, and investors that the competition for artificial intelligence (AI) and other digital development would increase social injustice if not accompanied by ethical assessments of public interests.
The Pope said at the Vatican Conference, where government diplomats, representatives of Facebook and Google, philosophers, physicists and ethics met.
A few scholars and Catholic bishops were invited to the conference entitled "Public Interest in the Digital Age."
The three-day conference was the latest evidence of the Vatican's willingness to participate in discussions of future and danger in artificial intelligence development.
At the conference, discussions were held on the future of wartime technology development and increased mechanical work, while case studies were conducted on gunfire incidents in Christchurch, New Zealand and the response of social media companies during the atrocities.
In his speech at the conference, the Pope praised the development of technological progress, citing how machines freed workers from danger and simple labor at the beginning of the Industrial Revolution.
However, if you rely too much on robotics to pursue profits, you may be afraid to take away the dignity of labor from humans.
The Pope warned, "If technological progress could cause increasingly prominent inequality, it would not be the right true progress."
If the so-called technological advances of humans are hostile to public interests, unfortunately, they will go back to a certain kind of savage based on the theory of the strong.
According to the organizers of the conference, they would like to take advantage of the expertise of the participants in the conference to find a person who can become a future adviser to the Catholic Church on the high-tech field.
