【Toba】10 Nepalese Minister of Agriculture and Forestry Dawa Dolce Rama visited Toba City Hall in Mie Prefecture and the recycling park in Daimeito-cho in Daimeito City on the 26th to observe the composting technology of raw garbage.
In the country, most of the waste used to be disposed of in landfills, but as a result of the introduction of the composting technology of garbage studied by Mr. Rio Hashimoto (67), a lecturer at the Japan Agricultural Management University, who lives in Tsu City through international students, the city of Timi, Kathmandu, started efforts to introduce waste recycling to model cities in order to promote organic farming without pesticides.
Since technology was utilized at the same facility in Toba City, which was established in 2007 in the prefecture, the tour began in February 30 and this is the third visit to the tour group.
Minister Dawa, who first participated in the tour, met Mayor Yoshiichiro Nakamura at the city hall, and said, "Japan's technology is advancing in the world, and I want to promote initiatives not only in Timi but throughout the country."
Mayor Nakamura said, "I'm surprised that I haven't been to the whole Toba citizen yet, and I want to continue exchanges of mind."
[Saga Torrential rains] Sharing mothers' experiences while raising children | Saga News
"Haguhagu" (Representative of Tomoko Tanaka) held a discussion on the experiences and lessons learned from the Saga torrential rain disaster at Ariake Public House in Sakata, the town on July 27.
About 20 mothers who are raising children think about the form of disaster prevention suitable for each household and summarize their awareness and requests for local governments.
Sanosato Kusumoto (32) in Kitamachi, Takeo City said that three-year-old children who liked the nursery school suddenly lost their desire to go to the nursery school after the flood, and they were forced to stay overnight.
"It's because adults are busy cleaning up the house and have not had enough time to face it," he said, "I want to prepare for a disaster so that adults can not panic and say "OK."
Mr. Yukari Ogushi (36) of Shiraishi-cho spent a night in a shelter town hall with four family members, including three-year-old children.
He said, "If you have a child who can't stay still, you will use your mind around you."
A woman in the center of Saga City (45), with five children between 4 and 12 years old, was soaked in water.
"I can't run away with five people," he said, "I'm going to spend my time at home as much as possible in a disaster and have food and a simple toilet.
"There is no correct answer to the preparation, and the necessary preparation changes in the situation of family structure and residence."
Ms. Shinako Kawasaki (40) of Shiraishi-cho, who has a child of 6 and 8 years old, proposed that "the elementary school had a closed school e-mail the day before, but the nursery school had no communication network or email system.
There were also requests to build a system that could share flooded roads in real time.
Mr. Kawasaki said, "The weather has changed from before, and I don't know what it was like last time."I want to prepare for disasters by taking care of small ingenuity and connections with people."
President Tanaka said, "I will think that the opinions presented will be conveyed to the government as an organization."
