more than 30 mobile games developed by nineyearolds in nigeria
The nine-year-old is using a free programming app called Scratch 2 to create a hide-and-do game.
Scratch 2 allows you to create games, anime and stories on and offline.
Basil has used this app to create more than 30 mobile games.
Today's game is a game programmed to hide bats.
Players get points when they catch bats that come out of hiding places.
He learned how to make a game in a short intensive course.
Basil told CNN that he spent time building games when he was bored.
In March, his father applied for a five-day intensive course for children aged 5 to 15.
The course, sponsored by Codefest International, was introduced to give children like Basil the opportunity to touch new technologies such as robotics and virtual reality.
According to his father, Basil Okpara Senior, Basil grew up playing many mobile games.
"When I was four years old, I bought a tablet.
Candy Crash and Temple Run did quite well," his father told CNN.
However, at the age of seven, Basil's interest in game production increased.
"One day I was playing a tablet as usual, but I was so absorbed in the game that I got a bit angry," his father said.
I was so frustrated that I said, "I'm always playing games, but what about making games myself so that others can play?"
When I said that, I was angry and I didn't think Basil really care."
Since then, Basil, who was interested in learning how to make his own game, asked his parents to buy a laptop and enrolled in a course to learn how to make a game.
Basil-chan, who wants to become a scientist in the future, names his game as it is.
One of the games, "Mosquito mash," can be purchased at the Google Play Store.
The youth population of Africa is the highest in the world, and if African innovation is achieved, young people like Basil will take the initiative.
Recently, two 12-year-old Nigerians have been recognized for creating robots that use program code to organize household chores.
In May, Akrobo won the 2019 Robofest Contest, a girls' high school team from Ghana who programmed boxed robots.
Africa's investment in Google and Microsoft's giant technology companies has increased, and Basil and his children are trying to become future programming stars.
