In the world's first attempt to raise the user's sense of happiness, some users soon seem to like other people's posts!
This change, following the launch of a similar test of Instagram in Australia in July, makes Good! an individual and only posters appear.
The new Facebook attempt will begin on Friday, and will soon begin in Australia.
Facebook Australia's policy manager, Mia Garrick, said the change was based on feedback from mental health professionals who thought the number of goodies would be the cause of social comparisons.
Garrick said, "We had very positive feedback from a number of affiliated bullying groups and mental health organizations."
It only removes numbers so that users can focus on the quality of interaction and content rather than the number of likes and reactions.
Garrick said that it is expected that users will be able to share with this platform more securely than they feel competitive.
Garrick stated that business operators on Facebook would receive the same metrics and insights they had access to.
In some countries, such as Australia, Canada, Brazil, New Zealand, Japan, Italy, Ireland, etc., the test was conducted, and it was too early to say that tests were conducted in the same way.
Facebook's Instagram does not announce when the test will end or whether it will remain unchanged.
"There was initially positive feedback on the Instagram experience, but now it's a step to listen and learn," Garrick said.
Garrick, who is in Australia, the world's training country, pointed out that Australia has very aggressive "technologically familiar" Facebook and Instagram users.
He said Australia is a great country to get really good feedback on whether this is a valuable experience for people or not.
