Opening of "Kiraboshi ★ Art Exhibition" Okayama Artwork of people with disabilities: Sanyo Shimbun Digital|san Digi
Paintings of "Kiraboshi ★ Art Exhibition" lined up in front of shops in Omotemachi Shopping Street
The 3rd Kiraboshi ★ Art Exhibition, which introduces works of art by persons with disabilities in Okayama Prefecture (sponsored by Okayama Disabled Cultural Arts Association, Sanyo Shimbun Social Business Group, and the organizing committee of the exhibition), opened on August 27 in the area of Omotemachi Shopping Street in Okayama City.
Works created with free ideas and expressions that are not bound by existing concepts gather and attract shoppers.
Okayama will be held at the Tamano venue from October 3 to October 5-14.
From all over the prefecture, 50 paintings, 17 paintings and 15 photographs have been exhibited.
The paintings are in front of each store, the shapes are in the Tenmanya underground town art space, and the photos are in line with the Asano camera.
Some of the works are printed on banners and displayed over the street from the top of the arcade.
His paintings are bold and colorful, and he is depicted with delicate brush strokes.
The design using familiar materials such as cardboard, clay, and umbrellas is unique, and photographs that color the four seasons such as autumn leaves and sunflowers attract attention.
Mr. Yukiji Iyogi, the executive committee member, and the chairman of the Prefectural Association for the Welfare of Persons with Disabilities, said, "I want many citizens to enjoy nature and art in a style that blends works into the city."
This exhibition has been held since 2017 as a result of the growing momentum to evaluate the works of people who have not received specialized education in art as "Art Brut."
This year, Okayama Art Exchange 2019 will be held at the same time as the support program for the Setouchi Triennale, which will be held from the 27th to the 28th.
On the 28th and 29th, there is a guided viewing tour of the work, live paint that can be used for general participation, and on the 29th there is a workshop where you can experience making small items such as earrings by cutting the edge of the boar leather.
(From left) ASA Amami Sports Academy
[Okinagarabu General Bureau] The NPO ASA Amami Sports Academy (President Akira Sonoda and Amami City) and the Okinagara Sports Club ELOVE (President Junya Maeda and Chinamachi) signed a partnership for the promotion of remote island sports on February 25.
In addition to actively cooperating in projects implemented by both organizations, such as training guidance for various competitions, we will also establish a mutual support system in terms of health management and prevention of injury, such as when children from remote islands travel outside the island.
Both groups mediate and send their own trainers and instructors for training related to sports and share information.
When a team of remote islands participates in a tournament outside the island, they work to resolve issues such as the difficulty of trainers in terms of travel expenses.
Specifically, in cooperation with the Kagoshima Sports Promotion Center, a general incorporated association of Kagoshima Prefecture, which cooperates with the ASA during the prefectural and other tournaments on the mainland, we will provide support to prevent the performance of the athletes from falling due to fatigue during boat trips and consecutive nights.
In addition, during the tournament on Amami Oshima Island and Okinagarabe Island, it is said that it will support players who come from outside the island by cooperating with local orthopedic hospitals and hospital officials.
On the 25th, the signing ceremony was held at Elabco in Chimei-cho, and President Sonoda and Maeda shook hands.
After that, both organizations co-hosted a training session with Athletic Trainer Yuichiro Hidaka.
Local sports boys, club leaders and parents learned how to use taping properly and how to prevent injuries.
Mr. Sonoda (52) said, "The purpose of the activities to eliminate the handicap of remote islands in terms of sports environment is common to each other, and there are many areas where we can cooperate.
Mr. Maeda (43) said, "It is very encouraging to have a partnership with a proven organization like ASA, and if you want to absorb good things to improve the sports environment for children in remote islands," he said.
