Lorraine Kelly: I was told that Glasgow accent would never succeed in the TV world.
Lorraine Kelly revealed in his Glasgow accent that he was told by TV station bosses that he would never succeed.
Before appearing on television for the first time, "I was so nervous," Kelly, 59 years old, recalled 35 years in the broadcasting industry.
"I was 25 years old and I was very nervous," she says.
I worked as an investigator at the BBC Scotland branch, and my boss told me that your Glasgow accent would never succeed in the television industry.
Before I took over the Glasgow office, I went to London to meet everyone on the TV-am team and to see where the show was broadcast.
I never forget Ann Diamond and Mike Morris were interviewing legendary actress Betty Davis that morning.
I couldn't believe I was in the same room as a living legend.
I found out that my favorite place is here.
Kelly began working as a reporter for local newspapers in East Kilbride, Scotland, and became a reporter for the TV-am Scotland branch in 1984.
In addition, Kelly served as the host of the show on GMTV, ITV's Breckfast and Daybreak, and later began a program named Lorraine.
In celebration of her 35th anniversary, she broadcast a special program that looks back on Kelly's most memorable scenes and interviews.
" passion and enthusiasm" and "curiosity" were the keys to survival in the television industry, and the moderator added, "You have to put it in your work."
You must be honest and sincere.
To do what you should do, to get interested and interested in various people.
Looking back on the news that struck me, Kelly revealed that the Dunbrane shooting was "very painful."
The day after that terrible incident that 16 students and teachers were killed, I didn't think many families of children who were killed or injured watched us live broadcast the show from Danbourne.
Pam Ross, who was killed by her mother and five-year-old daughter Joanna, personally told me that she wanted to see me, so we spoke at her house for hours.
Not taking it all on the show, I went to Joanna's funeral, Pam and I've been friends since.
Kelly also interviewed the couple in 2007 when Kate and Gary McCann's daughter Madeleine were missing, stating that it was "very hard" and that "we really respect the strength and courage of the couple."
The couple must endure the painstaking nets that do not know what is happening to their beloved daughter.
The couple is not really sorry.
Lorraine's 35th anniversary program is broadcast on ITV from 8:30 a.m. on Monday, September 30.
Zimbabwe, Chiwenga, fearing traps.
According to government officials, Vice President Constantino Chiwenga declined the offer of a presidential post from former President Robert Mugabe in the midst of a political change due to fears that it might be a trap to refute the military action in November 2017.
During the coup, the Zimbabwe Independent reported last week that Mugabe offered Chiwenga to cede President while negotiations between Mugabe and the Defense Forces continued.
However, Chiwenga declined the offer, not because of anxiety, but because he saw the intention of Mugabe to use Chiwenga to inform the leaders and African Unions around the world that he was deprived of his administration in a coup.
According to a series of tweets by Jamwanda2, which confirmed that officials were senior officials of the Cabinet Office, "Mugabe, who had been in power for 37 years, is willing to cede the government to Chiwenga instead of Emerson Munnagagwa," it is said that intense negotiations were held at that time.
Mugabe, who realized he was losing power, told the government officials that he had made contact with Chiwenga by an envoy.
According to government officials, arbitration between the military headquarters and the late and former presidents was carried out by three persons.
It was reported that President Spokesman George Charamba, then head of the Central Intelligence Agency, Aaron Nepera, and Roman Catholic bishop Fidelis Muconoli were involved in the negotiations.
Gideon Gono, the former Governor of the Reserve Bank of Zimbabwe, was one of Mugabe's delegated roles in delivering the president's seat to the commander of the Zimbabwe Defense Forces Tiwenga alone.
Mugabe, who became a symbol of Africa after his death than he was alive, attempted to denounce military action by the African Union, seeking intervention by African leaders, but failed.
The offer to cede the presidency to the former CDF was not due to the choice of the former president.
"It was a wasteful act to start fatigue in part of the late president's family and to save the dangerously rapidly expanding situation," he wrote.
However, there were a few political aims of the late president, who wanted to change the flow at least diplomatically.
If there was anything to destroy the constitutional order, it would have been to clash with the African Union's view of the coup, but I want you to remember that the commanders had declared that they would not break the constitutional order and would not break it.
The late President, Mugabe, hoped that Chiwenga, the top military officer of the time, would be trapped and crush the claims of the commanders claiming that he did not break the constitutional order.
The late President Mugabe hoped that the African Union, which had not yet fully grasped the whole situation, would decide whether to position it as a coup, would eventually be called a coup, and that military intervention requests would be considered valid.
That was the intent and calculation underlying this offer.
The authorities say that Mugabe moved when he realized that he was not protected by the defense forces.
He was warned that he would be executed like Kadafi, and Mugabe said he had to write a resignation letter.
The commanders of the military told Mugabe that even if they had penetrated the presidential house called Blue Roof, they would not point guns to the citizens.
At that point, Mugabe said he wanted two things: to protect his family, and to prove his military deprivation.
The commanders and commanders of the time accurately read their intentions.
A powerful metaphorical expression was used in the words of an envoy (Gono) telling the president's desperate message: "Is Tiri Bemaqwapa Macwapa (we belong to the camouflage group or military unit) and we are not politicians or political competitors."
The Army told the other commanders of the region that through the military officers who were staying in Zimbabwe, the objective was not to defeat Mugabe but to remove the "criminals" surrounding him.
In order to discuss the coup and successors, Mugabe attempted to bring back Munnagagwa, a short-term exile in South Africa, using the same method.
In addition to negotiations with the Army, Mugabe needed assistance from the region.
Not only had economic power and regional power, but also because President Jacob Zuma was the chairman of the Southern African Development Community at the time, the key South Africans in this process had refused to intervene, but, as repeatedly threatened behind it, clarified that the South African army would be immediately sent to Harare if the military had invaded the presidential house.
"Just because it wasn't supported by President Putin and African leaders, it didn't come to fruition," the sources state.
