Same-sex marriage justice judgment The opportunity to broaden diversity: Hokkaido Shimbun
The Utsunomiya District Court's Maoka Branch made a decision to approve the case in which 'in fact marriage' (internal marriage) that conforms to marriage could be established between same sex.
There are more than 20 countries that recognize same-sex marriage, and there is a system in which local governments such as Sapporo City certify same-sex partnerships, which are not legally effective in Japan.
The decision was based on the fact that two women were actually married.
It is considered to be the first judicial decision to grant legal protection to same-sex couples.
The same-sex marriage is not permitted due to the provisions of the Civil Code and the Family Registration Law, and lawsuits are filed in five district courts, including Sapporo, to seek compensation for damages to the country as unconstitutional.
I would like to deepen my understanding of the rights and security of sexual minorities and discuss the legal system to recognize the various forms of families.
The women lived together for about seven years and obtained a marriage certificate in the United States, but the plaintiffs filed for damages to their former partners after they were found guilty.
The decision was based on the results of the two living together and recognized "the reality that is different from the actual marriage between men and women."
It is a revolutionary decision to extend the recognition of factual marriages that have the same rights as marriage in social insurance.
What is more important is the interpretation of Article 24 of the Constitution, which defines marriage as "only based on the agreement of both sexes."
It is said that "the same-sex marriage was not expected at the time of establishment, so it is not understood as the purpose of denying same-sex marriage."
While the Constitution does not assume same-sex marriage, it is expected that it will be a driving force for same-sex marriage lawsuits in various parts of the country.
On the other hand, because same-sex marriage was not allowed, the problem remained that the amount of compensation was reduced as "the benefits of legal protection differ from that of men and women."
It may not be difficult to distinguish the right to protect, while recognizing the same reality as between men and women.
According to a nationwide survey of domestic trends for married women, 70 percent of people believe that same-sex marriage should be recognized by law.
As lifestyle diversification progresses, if law is bound by traditional family images, it will take away the rights of those who do not fit it.
In fact, marriage is not a legal spouse, so there are still few restrictions, such as not receiving preferential treatment in the tax system and not having joint custody.
In consideration of same-sex marriage, it is necessary to review family legislation from a variety of perspectives, including not only marriage between same-sex couples but also the expansion of legal rights for actual marriage.
