<New sports on September 27>
the serious pollution of popular tourist spots, obviously in videos
Sydney Harbour is one of Sydney's largest tourist attractions, bringing $2109 million to the Australian economy every year, with opera houses, Circular Key, Luna Park and some of the most famous Harbor Bridges.
But under the bridge there is an ugly truth.
Sydney's famous port is one of Australia's worst waterways, with about 15 cups of contaminants in the Olympic pool every year.
Thanks to this terrible statistics, one of our biggest tourist attractions is one of the dirtyest places.
According to a new video titled "From Sydney Harbour to Down," the waterways around Australia's most popular cities are filled with shells, plastic bags and plastic bottles, shoes and clothes lost by someone, and even animal corpses - all due to rainwater flowing through the road.
The biggest factor that clogs the waterway is plastic.
Coincidentally, the video was released on September 27 of the World Tourism Day, and Dr. Katherine Dafoon, vice president of the Sydney Harbour Research Program, said, "This is paradox."
Although its appearance is certainly beautiful, it is one of the most polluted estuaries of the coastline of Japan.
According to CSIRO, 1560 kilograms of plastic per hour is expected to flow into the waterway, most of which flow through the rainwater drain into Sydney Harbour.
"There were heavy rains several times, but Sydney Harbour was... quite tragic," Dr. Daffon said.
Two-thirds of the pollution comes from rainwater flowing through the road surface.
However, it is a part of the iceberg, and under the surface of the Sydney Harbour, 70 percent of the plastic that flows into the ocean is deposited in the seabed.
"If you don't actually go under the sea level, you don't know what's there," said Richard Nichols, owner of the Dive Center Manley, who collects about 500 kilograms of plastic waste each year by himself and his team.
If a lot of people know more (what's under the surface of the water), I think everyone will be really surprised.
Over half of what we discover is plastic bags.
The other half is plastic at least somewhere.
Sydney Harbour is beautiful at first glance, and no one can believe that all of these plastics and garbage are flowing right under the water.
Jeremy Brown, one of Ocean Protect's founders and director, said that local residents and tourists may be able to reduce plastic and garbage flowing into the waterways.
he says, we should start from the source.
It reduces plastic usage, recycles better, and eventually flows into the sea, so you have to focus more on what is flowing into the drain.
50 percent of the oxygen we breathe comes from the ocean, so hurting the ocean will kill us.
The oceans absorb 30% of carbon dioxide and are food sources.
However, we can repair Sydney Harbour and return it to its old appearance, but it is very simple.
killing the sea means killing people.
A new study on plastics and mental health was also presented this month, coincided with the release of the video funded by the recycling company TOMRA, as part of a broader awareness of environmental protection and the reduction of the impact of beverage containers that remain in the natural environment.
According to a new study, 82 percent of 546 children between the ages of 12 and 18 have a feeling of despair about plastic waste, and 25 percent believe that disposable plastic waste is an adult's fault.
The study also stated that 93 percent of 551 parents surveyed were increasingly concerned about the amount of plastic waste flowing into the ocean.
Most of the participants said they wanted to do something about plastic waste, but they didn't know how to change it, which led to ecological anxiety.
The former Karatsu Power Plant was demolished in October | Saga Shimbun News|Saga Shimbun
The chimney of the former Karatsu Power Station, which began demolition work in October, is Futako, Karatsu City.
Kyushu Electric Power Co., Ltd. announced on October 26 that it would begin dismantling the chimneys of the former Karatsu Power Plant (oil-fired power plant) in Futako, Karatsu City.
Construction is expected to be completed by the end of March 2021.
It is about 180 meters high, two of which were used to generate electricity.
The original three were removed in 1991.
One of the chimneys is broken down by a tower crane.
The plan takes nine months for each decomposition and takes 18 months.
The remaining turbine buildings and boilers have not been demolished.
A man in his 60s who runs a restaurant nearby said, "When I look back from afar and see a chimney, it is like a symbol that made me feel like I came back to Karatsu.
The former Karatsu Power Plant began operation in 1967, and the first was abolished in 89 and the second was abolished in 2015.
It is located in a corner of Karatsu Higashi Port, and has an area of approximately 225 thousand square meters.
Due to the proximity of Yacht Harbor and JR Nishi Karatsu Station, the prefecture and the city want to use the site.
Three people, including nine electric cars, signed an agreement on the use of the site in 15 years.
Product development with local fish tail eagle high selling fish nuggets Mie - Ise Shimbun
[Students who promote fish nuggets and rice cooked in Thailand] At Owashi High School in Furutono-cho, Owashi City
[Owashi] Four third-year students from the Department of Information Business at Owashi High School in Furutono-cho, Owashi City, Mie Prefecture developed fish nuggets and rice cooked in Thailand using locally caught fish.
It was sold at the school's cultural festival on August 26.
It is part of the Mie University Tokishu Satellite High University Project, which is engaged in the revitalization of the water industry and forestry industries, which are local industries in the Tokishu region.
The products developed include fish nuggets made from molts that are caught in the Kumano Nada and rice cooked using aquaculture die from Owashi.
It is said that he targeted young people.
Fish nuggets developed three types of fish nuggets, including tofu and gas shrimp from Owashi.
In cooperation with Kumano Fishery Co., Ltd., he wears it at a processing plant in Yugi-cho, Kumano City.
Thai rice is mixed with shiitake mushrooms and carrots.
"Odeo fish Ichibaoto" (Kotono-cho, the same city) is in charge of cooking.
Classes began in June.
They visited the Owashi factory and deepened their understanding of the water industry.
The workshop discussed consumer needs and tried prototypes.
He also invented naggets using azigs, but he adopted mutz because of the smell peculiar to fish.
Mr. Masaki Yamaguchi (17) said, "It's a product that can be eaten by people who are not good at fish, and I'm glad that many people can eat it."
It is said that they are negotiating with tourist facilities in the city to sell their products.
