The World Rally Championship will be held in Japan in November 2020.
It is the first edition of the Yahoo! News.
The World Rally Championship will be held in Japan in November 2020
The FIA announced on September 27, 2019 that the FIA World Rally Championship Japan Round will be held in Aichi Prefecture and Gifu Prefecture on November 22, 2020.
Look back at past WRC World Rally Championship with images!
18 cards.
The last event in Japan was held in Hokkaido in 2010.
What is the WRC that will be revived in 2020?
The WRC World Rally Championship, along with Formula One (F1) and the World Endurance Championship, is one of the four World Championships under the jurisdiction of the FIA.
Since 1973, it has been the world's highest rally championship with history and tradition, and the competition is said to be the toughest car championship because it is not only closed public roads (paved roads), but also gravel roads and snow roads.
In the 2018 season, Toyota won the WRC Manufactures title for the second season since 1999 and became a big topic.
This time, the Japan Round Invitation Preparatory Committee was established to host Japan.
As a result, it was decided that the 2020 WRC Japan Round will be held at the World Motorsport Council, the highest voting body of the International Automobile Federation.
Mr. Akio Toyoda (President and CEO of Toyota Motor Co., Ltd.), the governors of Aichi Prefecture and Gifu Prefecture, and general representative of TOYOTA GAZOO Racing WRT, said the following.
Mr. Hideaki Omura, Governor of Aichi Prefecture
"We sincerely welcome the FIA World Rally Championship to be held in Japan in 2020, and we will work together with stakeholders to ensure that the FIA World Rally Championship will be held in Japan in the fall of 2020 as the center of motorsports representing Japan, and that it will be a big appeal to the world."
Mr. Hajime Furuta, Governor of Gifu Prefecture
"I am very pleased that the Japanese round of the FIA World Rally Championship will be held here in 2020, where the Tokyo Olympic and Paralympic Games will be held.This is the first global motor sports tournament in the prefecture, and I am looking forward to seeing you all."
Mr. Akio Toyoda (President and CEO of Toyota Motor Co., Ltd.)
"I am very happy to run Yaris WRC in Japan.
Thank you for your support."
In addition, Mr. Keiji Furuya, Chairman of the Federation of Motor Sport Promotion Members, commented on the Japan Round.
The WRC World Rally Championship will be held from 19 to 22 November 2020.
The area is a public road in Aichi Prefecture (Nagoya City, Okazaki City, Toyota City, Shinjo City, Nagakute City, Shitara Town) and Gifu Prefecture (Nakatsugawa City and Ena City).
The main venue has been announced to use the "Love - Earth Expo Memorial Park (Nagakute City: commonly known as Morikoro Park) " which was opened on the site of the 2005 Japan International Exposition.
In addition, the Japan Round Preparation Committee will hold a decision-making meeting at the Tokyo Motor Show 2019 venue, and the Central Rally Aichi/Gifu 2019 test event will be held on November 9 and 10, 2019.
is Tasmanian devil the key to cancer treatment?
Tasmanian devil may be the key to cancer treatment - researchers have opened a breakthrough that could lead to major reforms in patient care.
Medical researchers found out how some cancer cells camouflage.
Researchers found that the same process occurred in Tasmania Devil and humans.
It is expected that this discovery will lead to new ways of treating cancer patients.
What is the commonality between Tasmanian devils and humans?
It is an invisible cancer cell.
A team of researchers, including researchers at the Peter McCallum Cancer Center in Melbourne, found that cancers that do not respond to immunotherapy could significantly alter their treatment for cancer.
It may also be the key to addressing deadly facial tumors that threaten the future of Tasmanian devils near extinction.
The study found that some cancer cells in humans and bags use a series of proteins called PRC2 to camfurage, causing markers to no longer react and immune systems to no longer attack cancer.
This is a major challenge for treating a type of skin cancer called small cell lung cancer, neuroblastoma and melkel cells.
Peter McCallum researcher Mark Dawson said, "What is very important in this project is that we may be able to reverse the process for patients who are resistant to immunotherapy."
Traditional therapies may be reused to reactivate markers, or proteins known as MHCs, and immune systems may be able to identify cancer cells.
"It may have a significant impact on lung cancer patients," Dawson said.
"Lung cancer is a disease prevalent in the world.
And it could be treated in a much better way.
Researchers hope that this discovery will eventually be used to treat face-to-face tumors in Tasmanian devils where similar cases of cancer cells escape detection.
"Unsurprisingly, exactly the same process occurs in humans and Tasmanian devil cancer," Professor Dawson said.
"It was very difficult to treat tumors in Tasmanian devils.
But if drugs that are effective in humans can be used in Tasmanian devils, they may be useful for controlling tumors."
scientists are puzzled by giant planets orbiting tiny stars.
Scientists have discovered and amazed the solar system, 30 light-years away from Earth, where giant Jupiter-shaped planets orbit around small stars called red dwarfs.
On September 26, 2019, an artistic image of the giant gas giant GJ3512b orbiting its main star, the red dwarf, was released.
Stars are usually much larger than the largest planets orbiting around them.
However, in this case, the size of stars and planets is not much different, the researchers said on Thursday.
The star, called GJ3512, is about 12 percent the size of the Sun, but the planet orbiting around it has at least half the mass of Jupiter, the largest planet in our solar system.
Juan Carlos Morales, an astrophysicist at the Catalan Institute of Space Studies at the Spanish Institute of Space Sciences, led the study published in the journal Science.
The theoretical model of formation shows that normally low-mass stars are the main stars of small planets similar to Earth and small Neptune.
In this case, we discovered a giant gas planet similar to Jupiter around a very small star."
The planet, composed primarily of gas, like Jupiter, was discovered using a telescope at the Calalto Observatory in Spain.
The planet orbits around the star for 204 days.
Red dwarfs are small and have relatively low surface temperatures.
The GJ3512 is not only considerably smaller than our Sun, it is almost the same size as the giant planet and only about 35% larger than Jupiter.
Because the emission energy is small, it is darker than the Sun, and the surface temperature is very low at about 3800 degrees Celsius (6380 degrees Celsius/3527 degrees Celsius).
That's why I have a reddish color."
While there is a sign that the second planet is currently orbiting the star, Morales said that the third planet may have been released from its stellar system in the past, explaining its elliptical orbit.
Planets are produced from the same disk, consisting of interstellar gas and dust that produced their own orbiting stars.
In the most powerful planetary formation model known as the "core accumulation" model, the object is formed from solid particles in the disk, and the attraction created by the egg of the planet causes the surrounding gas to become the atmosphere.
A conflict model called a self-gravity instability model may explain this unusual planetary system.
"In this case, the protoplanetary disk surrounding the newly born star may have been slightly larger and less temperature than was thought," Morales said.
Since the disk becomes unstable in this state, some dense regions may also appear.
These masses can grow until they collapse and form planets.
