Alfa Laval received orders for 100 million Swedish krona natural gas projects.
Alfa Laval, one of the world's leading heat exchangers, centrifuge separation, and water treatment companies, received an order to supply air cooling equipment to a natural gas treatment plant in the United States.The project is about 100 million Swedish krona and is scheduled to be delivered in 2020.
The project includes the Alfa Laval Niagara air cooling system, which will be used as part of a cooling system to separate natural gas from individual pure materials - ethane, propane and butan.
Safety is important in all industrial processes, but it is extremely important for careful natural gas processing.
"Our reliable air cooling equipment is rated for safety performance that customers can feel at ease," said Suzanne Paren Okrund, Head of Energy.
As you may know, ethane, propane and bethane are separated from natural gas, and can then be used as raw materials for petrochemical plants, household heaters, or as fuel for vehicles.
about alpha laval.
Alpha Laval is the world's leading supplier of special products and engineering solutions based on heat exchange, separation and water treatment.
Alfa Laval's facilities, systems and services are designed to help customers optimize their manufacturing processes.
The solution helps customers heat, cool, separate and transport products in the food and beverage, chemical, petrochemical, pharmaceutical, starch, sugar and ethanol manufacturing industries.
Alfa Laval's products are used in power plants, ships, oil and natural gas exploration, mechanical engineering and mining, as well as in wastewater treatment, air conditioning and refrigerators.
Alfa Laval organizations around the world collaborate with customers from around 100 countries to help customers lead the international community.
Alfa Laval is a listed company in Nasdaq OMX and in 2018 it recorded annual sales of approximately 40.7 billion Swedish krona (about €4 billion).
The number of employees is approximately 17200.
5 Medical Institutions in Saga Prefecture | Administrative and Social News|Saga Shimbun
The Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare (MHLW) announced the name of the hospital on March 26 that five public medical institutions in Saga Prefecture need to be reorganized and integrated.
Of the 13 medical institutions surveyed in the prefecture, 38 and 5% are the 10th highest in Japan, and three have already been integrated and relocated.
The hospital is named after the National Hospital Organization Higashi-Saga Hospital (Miyaki-cho, Miyoki-gun), Takyu City Hospital (Takyu City), Kojo Municipal Hospital (Kojo City), Imari Matsuura Hospital (Imari City), Regional Medical Function Promotion Organization (Imari City), and Tatara Hospital in Taramachi, Fujitsu County.
Of these, Takyu City Hospital and Kojo Municipal Hospital are planning to build a new hospital in Higashi-Takyu-cho, Takyu City, and Imari Matsuura Hospital has been relocated to Matsuura City, Nagasaki Prefecture.
Taira Hospital is the center of community comprehensive care in the town, and has been operating in surplus for several years.
Mayor Takayuki Nagabuchi emphasized that "As a town, we have the idea of operating alone and collaborating with hospitals in neighboring cities, and hospitals must be left absolutely for residents," and expressed negative views on reorganization and integration.
The administrative director of Higashi-Saga Hospital said, "We do not hear the contents from the prefecture," and concluded that "We will actively participate in the regional medical concept coordination meeting of the prefecture and respond to it based on the purpose of the discussion."
The Organization for Promotion of Regional Medical Functions (Tokyo), which operates Imari Matsuura Hospital, said, "The announcement is not a mechanical decision to determine the direction of public hospitals, but a request was made at the Regional Medical Design Coordination Conference in each prefecture to review them again."
"We would like to hear from the parties about the future operation of the hospital.
In some cases, we may ask you to review your medical courses and to further reduce your sickbed."
