Floods and disruptions caused by prolonged monsoons in many parts of India
The monsoon season in India has been prolonged for about a month, with unprecedented rainfall causing buildings to collapse and death, and many crops are beginning to rot.
Monsoons in northern India usually weaken their power in early September, but the average rainfall this month is 37% higher than usual.
According to experts from the Indian Meteorological Agency, if this situation continues for a few days, the monsoon will weaken at the latest decades.
Many parts of India still have unprecedented rains, and the latest news is that in Pune, western India, the buildings collapsed due to heavy rains on Wednesdays and Thursdays, killing several people.
The houses were flooded, and the inhabitants crossed the street with water on their knees, usually seen only at the height of the monsoon.
Other cities such as Kolkata, Raknau and Hyderabad also suffered heavy rains.
In northern Uttarakhand, heavy rains have caused significant damage to houses.
The arrival of Monsoon was too late.
With water shortages in many areas, farmers were preparing for possible droughts.
Long-lasting monsoons are not desirable for farmers.
This rainfall is not uncommon at this time.
Prakash Mehera, a small farmhouse in Bimtar, Uttarakhand, said, "We are currently making cabbage, beans, peas and tomatoes, but the vegetables will rot in the rain."
For consumers, the price of onions that cannot be used in Indian cuisine will rise due to the slow and weak monsoons.
In cities such as Delhi and Mumbai, 20 rupees (23 pence) of onions are usually sold at 80 rupees per kilogram.
The festival is also in danger.
The next big festival is in Dashera on 8 October, where the Hindus set up a giant comic book-style doll, Ravana, the evil smiling figure of the beard-boo appearing in the epic Ramayana.
The burning of Ravana means that good destroyed evil.
However, since the doll is made of paper, if Monsoon pulls long, the last laugh may be Lavana.
