Exposure to large amounts of pesticides can increase the risk of heart disease and heart attack
Current studies have shown that working near high concentrations of pesticides may increase the risk of heart disease later.
This was the result of a survey of Japanese Americans living in Hawaii for over 30 years.
Compared to men who did not work around pesticides, researchers found that the risk of heart disease and heart attack increased by 45 percent.
"The emphasis on this study is the importance of wearing personal protective gear when exposed to pesticides at work, describing the presence of pesticide exposure at work in medical records, and reducing the standard risk factors of heart disease," says Dr. Beatrice Rodriguez, co-author of the study.
Dr. Rodriguez is a professor in the Department of Elderly Care at the University of Hawaii in Manoa.
This is the result of research on data collected from more than 6,000 men living in Oahu who participated in the Kuakini Honolulu Heart Program.
The study focuses only on Japanese Americans, and researchers say that it may not be applicable to women or other races.
Because pesticides have a long half-life, health effects may appear years after exposure.
The study had the greatest impact within 10 years of exposure.
"As a result of 34 years of tracking, the relationship between exposure to pesticides and heart disease and heart attack at work is no longer important," Dr. Rodriguez said.
This is probably due to the increased importance of other factors related to aging and the possible relationship between pesticides and heart disease in later years.
Researchers found that exposure to low- and medium-density pesticides was not important for heart disease and heart attack.
