Ghana won two awards at the International Civil Aviation Organization.
Ghana won two prestigious awards at the 40th ICAO General Assembly in Montreal, Canada.
The safety award was awarded to Ghana, who provisionally received 89.89% of the effective implementation rate and was awarded the highest score in Africa by Air Safety Director.
Prior to this, ICAO completed its coordinated verification survey (ICVM) on 3 April 2019 in accordance with the World Safety Director Audit Report of the United Nations Air Force.
The safety award is a result of the recognition that Ghana complies with the standards and agreements recommended by ICAO for safety at airports and national airspace.
These awards were created as part of the ICAO's delayed National Zero Campaign.
In addition, 16 certifications for safety evaluation and 17 certifications for safety evaluation were awarded to ICAO participating countries with improved safety standards.
The award was awarded to Joseph Kofi Ada, Minister of Aviation of Ghana, Simon Alati, Director General of Civil Aviation of Ghana, Ambassador Nii Aikoi Otou of Ghana to Canada, and director of Yau Kuwakwa Ghana Airport Company.
In his speech, Chairman of the Board of Directors of the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO), Olmiwa Bennard Aliou stressed the need to maintain aviation safety in participating countries.
"It is important to always be aware that aviation safety, security and sustainability are still the most fundamental priorities in this era of innovation."
Mr. Ada said that this award complements the indomitable efforts and perseverance of the sector and is a gift of Ghanaian efforts.
